        <!-- PART 2 -->
        <div class=""tab-pane fade"" id=""part2"">
            <br />
            <p>
                When we combine the two components (mass and speed) together, it's easy to imagine moving something
                heavy at a high speed requires a lot of energy, and something with very little mass at a high speed
                requires a lot less energy.
            </p>
            <p>We can show this mathematically.</p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    The average weight of a midsize car in the UK is 1600 kilograms (1.6 tons). We will keep the mass the same
                    and change the value of speed to compare the differences in the kinetic energy of an object.
                </li>
                <li>
                    Whilst it's stationary (0 metres per second), it would have no kinetic energy because anything multiplied
                    by zero is still zero.
             ");
            WriteLiteral(@"   </li>
                <li>
                    The speed limit in a UK town is 30 mph, but we're going to use 25mph (11 metres per second).
                </li>
                <li>
                    The speed limit on a UK motorway is 70 mph, but we're going to use 50mph (31 metres per second).
                </li>
                <li>
                    The speed for an instant ban is in excess of 100 mph (45 metres per second).
                </li>
            </ul>
            <p>We will now put these numbers into the equation with an explanation below.</p>

            <div class=""row justify-content-center"">
                <div class=""card bg-light mb-3"" style=""max-width: 60rem;"">
                    <div class=""card-header"">25 miles per hour</div>
                    <div class=""card-body"">
                        <h1 class=""card-title"">E<sub>k</sub> = ½mv<sup>2</sup></h1>
                        <p class=""card-text"">We need to change the m and the v to the relevant numbers ");
